@node "About EZBackup"


     So what's all this fuss about? Another backup utility? Come on pal, there
are so many of these, which are probably better than this one, with more
functions. Why did you bother, really?

     Well, would you believe it or not, but I never found a PD/shareware backup
utility that would fit my requirements. Some of them backup only to disks (yeah,
try to backup a 1.2Gb Hard Drive on disks!), others have problems with AFS, many
often ask for a shareware fee (let's be serious, everyone can copy files with
DOpus!). I recently got Quaterback6.1 on a cover CD, and it has problems making
backups of more than 10Mb... Okay so maybe I haven't understood how it works, or
I forgot to configure it correctly. But that's exactly the point! Most of the
time you only need a utility to crunch and copy some important files to your EZ
drive or your Zip drive, without too many fuss. That's exactly what EZBackup
does.

     The features:
     - It's easy 
     - It does backups easily 
     - It's easy on your wallet coz' it's free :) 
     - It's easy ... did I mention that already?

     The trick of EZBackup is that there's no trick! It is completely OS legal.
EZBackup creates a script for you (a LOG), compresses for you using lha, lzx,
etc... You could do the same thing by writing a dos script. But why bother? 
     Now version 2 also allows you to configure the lha/lzx command line, so if
you dont like the way it works, you just change the script. Honestly, what more
do you want?... Apart from a lot of dosh and chicks galore (no offense to you
ladies!).      


@endnode


@node "Requirements"


    EZBackup uses GadTools to create an accessible and intuitive user interface
(man, I'm starting to talk like those Microsoft guys!). GadTools first appeared
in Amiga's OS2.0, so it should work fine with OS2.0 or superior. Still if I were
you, I'd try to get the lastest version of the library, as I only tested
EZBackup on my OS3.0 Amiga.
    It also uses ReqTools from Nico François, implemented in Blitz by Neil
O' Rourke. There again, get the lastest version of ReqTools available.
    Also by Neil is the progress bar, which also uses ReqTools.

    You'll need probably lha and/or lzx installed, unless you only want to use
the COPY mode. In that case you'll only need to have your WB installed... in
case you hadn't guessed it.

    I wrote and tested EZBackup on a 060 50Mhz with 26Mb of memory, a 1.2Gb HD
and WB3.1 (OS3.1). Running on the background: VirusZII, MagicCopper, MagicMenu,
ToolManager and MCP.

    If you have problems running EZBackup, try to deactivate background tasks,
to update your libs, etc... If this doesn't work, send me an E-Mail giving me
all the details: what are your specs, how did it happen, exactly WHAT happened,
what could you see on the screen, the symptoms, etc... The more complete you
are, the more are the chances I can help you.
    But that should happen. My program is perfect (Oh my, I did it again! I am
the master of the universe, yeeehaaa!).


@endnode


@node "Changes"


     Well let's see...
     There are some more options, and some of them aren't implemented 'coz
they're just a bunch of ideas I got, so I put them in shade mode (aka not
accessible) for possible future updates. 
     The new features are:
     - Backup mode selection: LHA/LZX and COPY
     - The advanced config option
     - The 'Clean Up !'button for the LOG list
     - Some minor bugs fixed
     - The title line now says 'EZBackup V2.0'. Hum...

     Okay so basically very little has changed. The COPY mode just copies the
files without compressing them. I thought that would be useful to backup your
Workbench partition, because it usually is smaller than 100Mb. If you need to
recover your Workbench volume, it'll be easier to copy it from a Zip disk
instead of decompressing it from an archive. That's instant recovery! 
     Some stuff has been added or changed according to the feedback I got (see,
it actually works!), like the lzx implementation. Some bugs have been corrected,
like if you started EZBackup in a screen smaller than 640x512 then the Amiga
would have gone GURU in most cases. 
     But as someone said (but I can't remember who): "A bug-less program is an
obsolete program". So keep sending me feedback and bug reports! 


@endnode


@node "Installation"


     Installation is easy enough:

     First enter the directory where the program is and position the mouse
pointer on the program's icon. DO NOT CLICK ON IT. Instead, press the following
keys in the following order: Left Shift, Left Ctrl, Left Amiga, Left Alt. Then
press the Help key SEVEN times, and say these words: "I thank Diego The Genius
for giving this wonderful piece of software for free. May he be blessed
forever". Next start jumping like a mad without releasing the keys (very
important) and finally bang your head against the nearest wall. That should do
it.




     ... or you could just copy EZBackup wherever you like and run it. Hey, why
don't you try both methods?




     No, better not try the first one...


@endnode


@node "Usage"


     Using EZBackup is real easy. Let's see how to backup your files step by
step:


     * Run the program by clicking twice on its icon (is it really necessary to
explain this? Oh well...). The first thing you'll see is a small welcome
requester. Click on the button to continue.


     * Oops, it's getting harder! Now you have three windows... 
     The first one is the main control window, with a few buttons to play with.
We'll examine them later. 
     The second window, called "Backup Progress Info" will give you some info on
what's going on during the backup process. 
     The third window is called "Actual LOG list". It is empty now, but it's
function is to show you the list of the files or directories to be included in
the backup when you press the "Backup!" button.


     * Allright, so let's see how to backup your entire Workbench partition:
     
     - First click on "New LOG" then click on "Yes". A nice requester will ask
you to select something. So click on "Volumes" and select your Workbench volume.
Be sure that there's nothing written in the "File" text gadget! 

     - Right, we just told EZBackup what part we actually want to backup, in
this case the entire Workbench partition. You should see now the line
"Workbench:" in the LOG window. 

     - We'll now select a destination path for the backup of the files. Click on
"Dest path" and select a path. This will usually be your EZ drive or Zip disk. 

     - Now select the compression mode: Lha, lzx or copy. Lha and lzx will
compress the whole volume using lha or lzx (you need to have installed them
first, of course!). Copy mode will just make a plain copy without compressing.
This is useful if your backup doesn't take too much space and can be fitted on
one Zip/EZ/whatever disk, because you'll have access to it without
decompressing.

     - Click on "Backup!" then on "Yes". A progress bar will appear and the
backup process will start. As easy as that. Note that the progress bar indicates
the evolution of in LOG list. As there's only one element in it, the progress
bar will be pretty useless in this case.


     * So what if you don't want to backup a whole partition? 
     
     Lets' take the Work partition. You have all your valuable data there, but
also some installed games, some demos coming from Aminet, etc... It's a bit of
useless to backup demos and games. So here's how to select the files to backup. 

     - Click on "New LOG" then "Yes". 

     - Now you're asked to select stuff to backup. Do so: if you want to select
a file, just find it and click on it. If you want to select an entire drawer,
then click on the drawer ONCE and eventually delete entirely the "File" text
gadget before clicking on "OK". 

     - You can keep adding files and directories by clicking on "Add to LOG".
     
     - Notice how each selection is added in the Log window. 

     - If you want to delete an entry from the LOG list then just click on it in
the Log window. A small requester will ask you to confirm the delete action. 

     - If you want to tidy up your list in alphabetical order, then click on the
"Clean Up !" button.
     
     - Done? Once you selected all the files and directories to backup, click on
"Save LOG". This allows you to save the LOG list you created, so next time you
backup you won't need to start it over again, unless files or directories have
been moved, renamed, or erased of course. 

     - Now select a destination path by clicking on "Dest path". Then click on
"Backup!" and here you go. Isn't that easy? 




     Basically, everything has been explained now. I told you it was easy!

@endnode


@node "Remarks"


     Please consider the following:
     
     
     - EZBackup has been conceived with removable medias in mind: EZ135, Zip,
Jaz,... The backup won't be splitted if the destination drive runs out of space.
So don't try to make backups on normal disks (unless you do a very small
backup!). 
    If you need to split your backup, you can either create two separate LOG
lists (according your backup is composed by various entries in the LOG list) or
modify the lha/lzx line config in the Advanced Config window to split the
archived file (I believe this option is available in the registered version
only... but I might be wrong. I actually never tried :)

     - The progress bar that appears when you hit "Backup!" is based on the
progression through the LOG files. This means that if you have 5 files in the
LOG, the bar will show 20%, 40%, 60%, 80%, and 100%. If you're doing a backup of
the whole Workbench partition, the bar is pretty useless indeed. I've been
suggested to make a bar that shows the real progress of the thing. Two reasons I
didn't: I wanted the bar to show my software's progression and not the
compressor's one, and I couldn't bother writing a recursive code to add files
progressively. Send me Ł500 and I'll do it :)

     - I wrote in the previous version that lha couldn't cope with spaces. It
seems it could... So sorry about that!

     - I noticed to my horror that my compressed backups had compression errors!
After some research, I came to the conclusion that the errors came from the AFS
system I installed on my EZ135 disks to speed up the thing. It seems like AFS
couldn't cope with large compressed files on an external media, though it works
brilliant on my HD! I didn't contact the authors, but I might have badly
configured the EZ in HDToolBox. So please check your archives after the backup!
I'll probably implement a lha check in a near future.

     - EZBackup surely isn't the most complete backup system in the world. But I
didn't want that. It does a simple job. The one I need to be done every time I
backup my HD. And it does it in a completely OS legal way, so it is (almost)
future proof. There.


@endnode


