easy! 
     Credits goes also to me for having programmed this software. Thanks to
Diego Pappalardo for being so modest... :)

     By the way, did you know EZBackup is Freeware? I mean, completely free for
you, my little Amiga user. I know, I know, I'm just soooooo kind!

     Why is it free? Well, I think if someone does a program mainly for himself
(and that's what happened here), he shouldn't ask for money unless that's a very
big thing that isn't similar to another good program. Also, I probably won't be
able to update EZBackup all the time, though I will eventually do updates like
this one from time to time.

     But remember, there are some very good shareware products out there. Maybe
you're using some of them all the time. So if you haven't done it yet, think
about registering the ones you use regularly, coz' if you use them then they're
good, and good software worth the little shareware fee the authors ask for. You
know, one day they might just get bored and go to PC land (noooooooooo!), the
land where a dumb screengrabber asks $20 of shareware fee. They're mad. I mean
it's just a screengrabber, geez! 
     Okay so promise me you'll think about it! It's more important now than
ever, because the Amiga is slowly rising again (though it's still a bit chaotic
by the time I write these lines), so your support is needed! NOW!


@endnode


@node "Reference guide"


    Here are all the functions explained:


    @{"New LOG" link "New LOG" 0}
    @{"Add to LOG" link "Add to LOG" 0}
    @{"Load LOG" link "Load LOG" 0}
    @{"Save LOG" link "Save LOG" 0}

    @{"Dest path" link "Dest path" 0}
    @{"LHA/LZX/COPY cycling gadget" link "LHALZXCOPY" 0}

    @{"Advanced config" link "Advanced config" 0}

    @{"Backup!" link "Backup!" 0}

    @{"Clean Up !" link "Clean Up !" 0}
    @{"- deleting files from LOG list -" link "LOGdelete" 0}


@endnode


@node "New LOG"


    This button clears the actual LOG list and starts a new one. Why I bother,
really!


@endnode


@node "Add to LOG"


    This allows you to add entries to the LOG list. If you want to delete
entries, just click on them in the 'Actual LOG list' window.


@endnode


@node "Load LOG"


    This loads a LOG list. The directory is set by default to SYS: , but I
personally prefer saving my LOG on the disk where my backup is. That's up to you
really...


@endnode


@node "Save LOG"


    Saves yout LOG to disk for future backups. Remember to check if you didn't
change some directory or files names, or they will be skipped without you being
noticed!
    Okay, so I'll write a directory check in the next update... Man' why didn't
I think that before?


@endnode


@node "Dest path"


    Opens a requester so you can specify where your backup is going to be saved.
This can be any disk or volume recognized by the OS!


@endnode


@node "LHALZXCOPY"


    This cycle gadget allows you to select the way you want to make your backup.
If you select LHA or LZX, the LOG items will be compressed accordingly, and you
will end with a bunch of archives named after the items. If you select COPY, the
items in the list will just be copied over.


@endnode


@node "Advanced config"


    This button opens a new window containing three text gadgets showing the
command lines used by EZBackup to process your LOG list. Basically, the 'lha'
gadget contains the commands passed to compress data in lha, etc...
    Internally, EZBackup then adds the directories or files of the LOG list at
the end of those lines and executes the resulting line like a cli command.
That's why EZBackup is totally OS friendly!
    Mind you, if you want to change the config in order to use another less
known packer, just delete one of the lines (for example, the lzx line) and type
the relevant commands. That makes me think: next update I'll just add a CUSTOM
gadget where you'll be able to type your custom command lines (like, for XPK or
such) without needing to alter the lha, lzx, or copy command lines. Don't ask me
why I didn't do it in this version: I just forgot!
    For those who hadn't guessed it: if you want, for example, to customize the
lha command line, just type the lha command like you'd do in a cli/shell window,
but don't type the source file/directory and the destination archive.
    To save your custom configuration, use the 'Save' button. EZBackup will
create a small prefs file in the directory from where it was launched. Every
time you'll run EZBackup, it will search for that prefs file, and if he founds
it then it'll be automatically loaded.


@endnode


@node "Backup!"


    This button is used to start your backup.
    Push it then cross your fingers :)


@endnode


@node "Clean Up !"


    This one cleans up the LOG list in alphabetical order.


@endnode


@node "LOGdelete"


    To delete entries from the LOG list, just click on the corresponding entry,
and a requester will ask you to confirm.


@endnode

